doctype html
html(lang='en')
  head
    meta(charset='UTF-8')
    meta(name='viewport', content='width=device-width, initial-scale=1.0')
    title How to Play Poker
    link(href='https://fonts.googleapis.com/css2?family=Poppins:wght@300;400;600&display=swap', rel='stylesheet')
    style.
      /* General Body Styling */
      body {
      background: linear-gradient(135deg, #121212 0%, #333333 100%);
      color: #fff;
      font-family: 'Poppins', sans-serif;
      margin: 0;
      padding: 0;
      line-height: 1.8;
      display: flex;
      flex-direction: column;
      min-height: 100vh;
      }
      /* Header Styling */
      header {
      background: linear-gradient(135deg, #f8c301 0%, #ff8700 100%);
      padding: 50px 20px;
      text-align: center;
      box-shadow: 0 4px 10px rgba(0, 0, 0, 0.5);
      position: relative;
      }
      header h1 {
      font-size: 3em;
      margin: 0;
      color: #fff;
      text-transform: uppercase;
      letter-spacing: 2px;
      text-shadow: 2px 2px 10px rgba(0, 0, 0, 0.3);
      }
      .home-button {
      position: absolute;
      top: 20px;
      left: 20px;
      background-color: #ff8700;
      color: #fff;
      padding: 10px 20px;
      font-size: 1.2em;
      text-transform: uppercase;
      border: none;
      border-radius: 5px;
      cursor: pointer;
      box-shadow: 0 4px 10px rgba(0, 0, 0, 0.3);
      transition: background-color 0.3s ease;
      text-decoration: none; /* This removes the underline */
      }
      .home-button:hover {
      background-color: #f8c301;
      }
      /* Main Content Area */
      main {
      max-width: 1000px;
      margin: 40px auto;
      padding: 40px;
      background-color: #222222;
      border-radius: 15px;
      box-shadow: 0 10px 30px rgba(0, 0, 0, 0.6);
      }
      section {
      margin-bottom: 30px;
      }
      h2 {
      font-size: 2.5em;
      color: #f8c301;
      border-bottom: 3px solid #f8c301;
      padding-bottom: 8px;
      margin-bottom: 20px;
      font-weight: 600;
      }
      p, ul {
      font-size: 1.2em;
      color: #e0e0e0;
      }
      ul {
      padding-left: 20px;
      margin-top: 10px;
      }
      li {
      margin: 12px 0;
      line-height: 1.6;
      }
      /* Hand Rankings Styling */
      .hand-ranking {
      display: none;
      padding: 20px;
      background: #333;
      border-radius: 10px;
      box-shadow: 0 4px 10px rgba(0, 0, 0, 0.4);
      }
      .hand-ranking img {
      max-width: 100%;
      border-radius: 8px;
      }
      .hand-ranking h3 {
      color: #f8c301;
      margin: 0 0 10px 0;
      }
      /* Arrow Navigation Buttons */
      .nav-buttons {
      display: flex;
      justify-content: center;
      margin-top: 20px;
      }
      .nav-button {
      background-color: #f8c301;
      color: #121212;
      padding: 10px 20px;
      font-size: 1.2em;
      font-weight: 600;
      border-radius: 30px;
      cursor: pointer;
      transition: background-color 0.3s ease;
      }
      .nav-button:hover {
      background-color: #ff8700;
      }
      .nav-button:disabled {
      background-color: #444;
      cursor: not-allowed;
      }
      /* Footer Styling */
      footer {
      text-align: center;
      padding: 20px;
      background-color: #1f1f1f;
      position: relative;
      margin-top: 40px;
      font-size: 1.1em;
      color: #d1d1d1;
      }
  body
    header
      // Home Button
      a(href="/")
        button.home-button Home
      h1 How to Play Poker
    main
      // Introduction Section
      section
        h2 Introduction to Poker
        p
          | Poker is a popular card game that combines skill, strategy, and luck. The objective of the game is to form the best possible five-card hand from the cards dealt to you and the community cards available. Players bet chips based on the strength of their hands, and the one with the best hand or the last person standing wins the pot.
      // How the Game Works Section
      section
        h2 How the Game Works
        p
          | In poker, each player is dealt two private cards (known as hole cards) and can use five community cards placed face-up on the table. The objective is to make the best possible five-card hand using any combination of the seven available cards. Players can bet, raise, fold, or check depending on the round.
      // Hand Rankings Section
      section
        h2 Hand Rankings
        // Hand Rankings Content
        #royal-flush.hand-ranking
          h3 Royal Flush
          img(src='https://www.888poker.com/magazine/sites/magazine.888poker.com/files/inline-images/Royal-Flush.webp', alt='Royal Flush')
          p A, K, Q, J, 10, all of the same suit.
        #straight-flush.hand-ranking
          h3 Straight Flush
          img(src='https://www.888poker.com/magazine/sites/magazine.888poker.com/files/inline-images/Straight-Flush.webp', alt='Straight Flush')
          p Five consecutive cards of the same suit.
        #four-of-a-kind.hand-ranking
          h3 Four of a Kind
          img(src='https://www.888poker.com/magazine/sites/magazine.888poker.com/files/inline-images/Four-of-a-Kind.webp', alt='Four of a Kind')
          p Four cards of the same rank.
        #full-house.hand-ranking
          h3 Full House
          img(src='https://www.888poker.com/magazine/sites/magazine.888poker.com/files/inline-images/Full-House.webp', alt='Full House')
          p Three of a kind and a pair.
        // Navigation Buttons
        .nav-buttons
          button#prev-btn.nav-button(disabled='') Back
          button#next-btn.nav-button Next
      // Betting Rounds Section
      section
        h2 Betting Rounds
        p
          | There are four betting rounds in Texas Hold&apos;em: Pre-Flop, Flop, Turn, and River. In each round, players have the option to bet, check, raise, or fold based on their cards and the community cards. The betting rounds provide players the opportunity to evaluate their hands and adjust their strategy accordingly.
      // Poker Tips Section
      section
        h2 Poker Tips
        ul
          li
            strong Pay attention to your opponents:
            |  Watching how others play can give you insight into their strategy.
          li
            strong Don&rsquo;t play too many hands:
            |  Be selective with the hands you play to avoid losing chips unnecessarily.
          li
            strong Know when to fold:
            |  Don&rsquo;t be afraid to fold a hand if you think you&rsquo;re beaten.
          li
            strong Use position to your advantage:
            |  Players acting later in the betting rounds have more information to make decisions.
    footer
